17 B. The ALJ’s S ubstantial Adoption of  the Public -Interest  Intervenors’ Proposed 
Findings Was Proper and Consistent with Her Rejection of the Petitioners’ 
Theory of the Case . 
The Petitioners contend  that the ALJ’s report is “copied from opposing parties’ proposed 
findings nearly word -for-word” and argue that this “show [s] a lack of independent judgment.”69  
They attach a redline d document showing the similarity of the ALJ’s findings to those proposed 
by Public Interest Intervenors.70  But i t should come as no surprise  that an ALJ would borrow 
heavily from the findings of the parties whose theory of the case she  agrees with .  And t here is 
nothing improper about a tribunal copying from  a party’s proposed findings —that is the whole 
point of proposed findings.  The ALJ’s findings are supported by substantial evidence and 
articulate a rational connection between the facts found and the conclusions reached, and the 
Commission should adopt them. 
It is a standard practice, both in trial courts and in administrative proceedings, for judges 
to ask parties to provide proposed findings.  “ Adoption of a party’s proposed findings by a district 
court is generally an accepted practice,”71 especially in cases “involving highly technical issues.”72  
It is even permissible for a trial court to adopt the prevailing party ’s proposed findings verbatim  
as long as  the findings are supported by the record.73  The rule is similar for administrative 
proceedings.  An agency may adopt a party’s proposed findings word- for-word as long as the 
findings are “specific and sufficient enough to enable meaningful review .”74

The Department of Commerce was the only party not to sign onto or submit any proposed 
findings .77  The two sets of proposed findings reflect diametrically opposed views of the proposed 
acquisition .  Having presid ed over a months -long administrative process, he ld a three- day 
evidentiary hearing, and consider ed the parties’ evidence and arguments, the ALJ ultimately 
agreed with the Public Interest Intervenors that the risks of the proposed acquisition were real and 
its benefits not well established.  It was therefore natural that she  would rely on their proposed 
findings.  Even so, the ALJ did not mechanically  adopt the Public Interest Intervenors’ proposed 
findings  without change;  instead , she incorporat ed them into her report with change s throughout .  
The Petitioners are unable to cite a case where  a court reversed an administrative agency’s 
adoption of proposed findings.  Instead, they selectively  reproduce  boilerplate from state and 
federal appellate- court opinions  to suggest that the practice  is disfavored.78  But the se opinions  
either upheld the adoption of  proposed findings79 or reversed based on facts dissimilar to this

appropriate , it should not take the drastic remedy of rejecting the ALJ’s report entirely  as the 
Petitioners advocate.  Instead, the Commission’s order can adopt the  report while supplementing 
it with any further findings the Commission deems necessary.

20 C. The Petitioners  Personally  Attack the ALJ Because They Disagree with Her 
Summary  of Public Comments.  
The Petitioners complain that the ALJ’s summary of public comments is one -sided because 
it notes that many of the comments supporting the acquisition “ largely repeated the Petitioner s’ 
employee and public messaging about the Acquisition” and that many supporters were Minnesota 
Power employees or community organizations that had received funds from Minnesota Power.82  
The Petitioners describe th e ALJ’s characterization  as “inappropriate and insulting” and conclude 
that the ALJ’s “ cavalier dismissal of the comments in support of the Acquisition is a sign of deep 
disrespect for the people in northern Minnesota who chose to make their opinions known” and  “a 
sign of troubling bias against the Acquisition and those supporting it.”83 
The Petitioners ’ criticism of  the ALJ  here crosses the line from zealous advocacy into an 
ad hominem  attack.  It is one thing to disagree with an ALJ’s characterization of public comments 
or other findings, but it is quite another to personally attack the tribunal in this way.  Nothing stated 
in the ALJ’s summary of public comments warrants  such an extreme response .  Far from the 
Petitioners ’ characterization, t he ALJ presided over a complex proceeding and rendered fair and 
impartial findings.  She performed her duties professionally, diligently, fairly and impartially , and 
certainly without bias or prejudice.84  The Commission should firmly reject the Petitioners’ 
uncalled -for attack on the ALJ’s character , professionalism , and judicial temperament .   
CONCLUSION 
Unable to persuade the ALJ of the merits of their case, the Petitioners lash out in an attempt 
to discredit her.  But nothing required the ALJ to believe the Petitioners’ evidence or arguments; 
indeed, she had a duty to fairly and impartially weigh the evidence and determine whether the 
 
82 Summary of Public Comments at 1. 
83 Petitioner Except ions at 18. 
84 See Minn. Stat. § 14.48, subd. 3(d); Minn. Code of Judicial Conduct R. 2.2, 2.3(A).  
21 proposed acquisition was consistent with the public interest.  Th at is exactly what she did.  She 
found that the Petitioners’ claims that “going private” held only benefits and no risks were 
overstated  and contradicted by the Petitioners’ own documents , most of which  the public is not 
allowed to see.  G iven the documented risks  and the unsubstantiated benefits , the ALJ  found that 
the acquisition would result in net harm to public interest.   
The Petitioners’ unjustified attack on a public servant is troubling and provides a glimpse 
of how new ownership could change Minnesota Power’s regulatory advocacy.  The Commission should find that this and other risks detailed in the ALJ’s report and the voluminous record render the proposed acquisition inconsistent with the public interest and deny its approval .
